ABUJA – The Independent National Electoral Commission (INEC) has reassured the international community of the determination of the commission to push the improved transparent conduct of elections in the country into the 2023 general election. INEC Chairman Prof Mahmood Yakubu gave the assurance when he received the European Union (EU) Election Observation Follow-up Mission to the Commission’s headquarters in Abuja. He told the mission led by Maria Arena, who also headed the EU Election Observation Mission to Nigeria’s General Election in 2019, that the nation’s Electoral system has benefited immensely from the deployment of technology since the last general election, among other numerous improvements. 2023: Why Zamfara APC Calls Saraki A failed Politician 2023: Tinubu Speaks On ‘Driving Vision’ As Next President Of… “The biggest progress made by the Commission since 2019 is in the area of deepening the deployment of technology in elections. INEC is the first electoral commission in West Africa, if not Africa as a whole, to upload Polling Unit level results to a portal in real-time on Election Day. “In addition, there are other portals for ease of nomination of candidates and submission of list of Polling Agents by political parties and the accreditation of media, domestic and international observers’ he stated. He also noted that the recently passed Electoral Act will further enhance the gains as it contains many progressive provisions that will further enhance the progress made. Prof Yakubu expressed his gratitude to the Commission for the EU support, noting that the various suggestions and recommendation from the mission in the area of administration, election management and Voter access has been invaluable. In her response, Maria Arena said the mission is happy with the remarkable achievement of the commission working with important stakeholders like members of civil society, and the country and hoped the effort will show in the next general election.